body:
Maybe already fixed in SNAPSHOT version. When executing:

```
class ConsoleDetailsTests {

	static abstract class A {

		@Test void mA() {}

		static class B extends A {
			@Test void mB() {}
		}

		static class C extends B {
			@Test void mC() {}
		}
	}

	@Test
	void issue771() {
		ConsoleLauncherWrapper wrapper = new ConsoleLauncherWrapper();
		ConsoleLauncherWrapperResult result = wrapper.execute(
				"--include-engine", "junit-jupiter",
				"--select-class", A.B.class.getName(),
				"--select-class", A.C.class.getName(),
				"--include-classname", ".*" // allow all class names, other than "^.*Tests?$"
		);
		System.out.println(result.out);
	}
}
```
...the console reads like:
```
╷
└─ JUnit Jupiter ✔
   ├─ ConsoleDetailsTests$A$B ✔
   │  ├─ mA() ✔
   │  └─ mB() ✔
   └─ ConsoleDetailsTests$A$C ✔
      ├─ mA() ✔
      ├─ mB() ✔
      └─ mC() ✔
```

`mA()` is executed twice. Running class B and C directly from within IDEA is working as expected, too.

Didn't check M3, yet.

The current implementation of [ReflectionUtils.findNestedClasses(...)](https://github.com/junit-team/junit5/blob/master/junit-platform-commons/src/main/java/org/junit/platform/commons/util/ReflectionUtils.java#L523) only considers **declared** class in the passed class. We could look up the class and interface hierarchy.

Like:

```java
List<Class<?>> candidates = new ArrayList<>();
for (Class<?> candidate = clazz; candidate != null; candidate = candidate.getSuperclass()) {
	Class<?>[] declaredClasses = candidate.getDeclaredClasses();
	if (declaredClasses.length > 0) {
		candidates.addAll(Arrays.asList(declaredClasses));
	}
}
// TODO add clazz.getInterfaces() recursively to candidates
return candidates.stream().filter(predicate).collect(toList());
```
